- Live culture verification (pasteurized = dead cultures)
- Starting doses and progression
- Histamine-intolerance considerations
- Homemade vs. store-bought quality

Gut Health Patterns
Pattern 1: Microbiome Diversity Reset
Building a healthy gut ecosystem:
- 30+ different plants per week (vegetables, fruits, legumes, nuts, seeds, herbs)
- Daily fermented food serving
- Progressive fiber increase (avoid sudden jumps)
- Polyphenol sources (berries, dark chocolate, green tea, olive oil)
- Minimize artificial sweeteners and ultra-processed foods

Pattern 2: Low FODMAP Implementation
Systematic IBS symptom management:
- Week 1-3: Strict low FODMAP elimination
- Week 4-8: Reintroduction by FODMAP group (fructose, lactose, fructans, GOS, polyols)
- Week 9+: Personalized FODMAP tolerance map
- Track symptoms with Bristol Stool Scale daily
- Work with healthcare provider for formal diagnosis

Pattern 3: Post-Antibiotic Recovery
Rebuilding after antibiotic course:
- Immediate: Saccharomyces boulardii (evidence for antibiotic-associated diarrhea)
- Week 1-2: Gentle probiotics + easily digestible foods
- Week 3-4: Reintroduce diverse fiber sources gradually
- Week 5-8: Fermented foods daily, diverse plant foods
- Monitor: Return of regular bowel patterns

Best Practices
Fundamentals
- Diversity beats quantity — many different fibers > lots of one fiber
- Introduce changes gradually — sudden fiber increases cause more gas, not less
- Hydration is critical for fiber to work properly
- Chew thoroughly — digestion starts in the mouth
- Stress management is gut management — the gut-brain axis is real

Tracking
- Food-symptom diary is the most powerful diagnostic tool
- Track: what you ate, when, how much, and symptoms 2-6 hours later
- Look for patterns over 2+ weeks, not single incidents
- Rate symptoms on a 1-10 scale for consistency
- Note stress, sleep, and menstrual cycle — they all affect digestion

Safety
- Gut symptoms can mask serious conditions — persistent symptoms need medical investigation
- Do NOT self-diagnose IBD, celiac disease, or SIBO — these need clinical testing
- Extreme restriction diets can cause more harm long-term — reintroduce always
- Probiotics are not universally beneficial — strain specificity matters
- Red flags: blood in stool, unexplained weight loss, severe pain → IMMEDIATE medical referral

